## Approach 3: Optimal (Stack-Based)

### Intuition

Addition works right-to-left, but the list is left-to-right. Push both lists onto stacks so we can pop digits from the least-significant end. Add with carry, then **prepend** each new node so the result list builds itself in the correct order — no reversing needed.

```python
def addTwoNumbers_optimal(l1, l2):
    s1, s2 = [], []

    while l1:
        s1.append(l1.val)
        l1 = l1.next
    while l2:
        s2.append(l2.val)
        l2 = l2.next

    carry = 0
    head = None

    while s1 or s2 or carry:
        val = carry
        if s1: val += s1.pop()
        if s2: val += s2.pop()

        carry, digit = divmod(val, 10)

        node = ListNode(digit)
        node.next = head       # prepend — builds list in correct order
        head = node

    return head
```

### Complexity

| | |
|---|---|
| **Time** | O(m + n) — one pass each to fill stacks, one pass to add |
| **Space** | O(m + n) — two stacks |

---

## Comparison

| | BF 1: Int Conversion | BF 2: Reverse Lists | Optimal: Stack |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Time** | O(m + n) | O(m + n) | O(m + n) ✅ |
| **Space** | O(m + n) | O(1) ✅ | O(m + n) |
| **Modifies input?** | No | Yes | No |
| **Extra data structures?** | Python int + str | None | Two stacks |
| **Interview preferred?** | No | Acceptable | Yes ✅ |

> BF 2 is actually the most space-efficient (O(1)), but it modifies the input lists — which interviewers may flag. The stack approach is the cleanest: no input mutation, no int/string tricks, pure linked-list logic.

